# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: qdrant
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p01] A key feature of Qdrant is the effective combination of vector and traditional indexes.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p01] It is essential to have this because for vector search to work effectively with filters, having a vector index only is not enough.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p01] In simpler terms, a vector index speeds up vector search, and payload indexes speed up filtering.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p01] The indexes in the segments exist independently, but the parameters of the indexes themselves are configured for the whole collection.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p01] Not all segments automatically have indexes.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p01] Their necessity is determined by the optimizer settings and depends, as a rule, on the number of stored points.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p01] Payload index in Qdrant is similar to the index in conventional document-oriented databases.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p01] This index is built for a specific field and type, and is used for quick point requests by the corresponding filtering condition.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p01] The index is also used to accurately estimate the filter cardinality, which helps the query planning choose a search strategy.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p01] Creating an index requires additional computational resources and memory, so choosing fields to be indexed is essential.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p01] Qdrant does not make this choice but grants it to the user.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p01] Payload indexes occupy additional memory and disk space, so it is recommended to only apply payload indexes for those fields that are used in filtering conditions.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p01] If you need to filter by many fields and the memory limits do not allow for indexing all of them, it is recommended to choose the field that limits the search result the most.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p01] As a rule, the more different values a payload value has, the more efficiently the index will be used.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p01] You can use dot notation to specify a nested field for indexing.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p01] Queries that filter on unindexed fields are not only slower; they can also unnecessarily consume cluster resources, negatively impacting the latency of other search queries.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p01] To prevent that, Qdrant provides an option to block queries that filter on unindexed fields.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p01] To block queries that filter on unindexed fields, enable strict mode and set `unindexed_filtering_retrieve` to `false`.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p01] Qdrant will then return an error if a search query attempts to filter on an unindexed field.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p01] On Qdrant Cloud, these settings are applied to all collections by default.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p01] For more information, refer to Disable Retrieving via Non Indexed Payload.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p01] We’ve added a parameterized variant to the `integer` index, which allows you to fine-tune indexing and search performance.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p01] The regular `integer` index assumes both `lookup` and `range` are `true`.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p01] Setting `lookup` or `range` to `false` may help to tune and reduce memory usage in large collections.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p01] We encourage you to try out if setting either to `false` improves memory usage.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p01] If you don’t see an improvement or if you’re not sure what kind of payload filters you’re using, use the regular `integer` index.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p01] Note: If you set `"range": false` and still use a range filter, it may lead to significant performance issues.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p01] The same is true for the lookup parameter and its respective filters.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p01] By default all payload-related structures are stored in memory.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p01] In this way, the vector index can quickly access payload values during search.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p01] As latency in this case is critical, it is recommended to keep hot payload indexes in memory.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p01] There are, however, cases when payload indexes are too large or rarely used.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p01] In those cases, it is possible to store payload indexes on disk.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p01] The list will be extended in future versions.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p01] Many vector search use-cases require multitenancy.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p01] In a multi-tenant scenario the collection is expected to contain multiple subsets of data, where each subset belongs to a different tenant.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p01] Qdrant supports efficient multi-tenant search by enabling special configuration vector index, which disables global search and only builds sub-indexes for each tenant.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p01] However, knowing that the collection contains multiple tenants unlocks more opportunities for optimization.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p01] To optimize storage in Qdrant further, you can enable tenant indexing for payload fields.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p01] This option will tell Qdrant which fields are used for tenant identification and will allow Qdrant to structure storage for faster search of tenant-specific data.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p01] One example of such optimization is localizing tenant-specific data closer on disk, which will reduce the number of disk reads during search.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p01] Similar to the tenant index, the principal index is used to optimize storage for faster search, assuming that the search request is primarily filtered by the principal field.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p01] A good example of a use case for the principal index is time-related data, where each point is associated with a timestamp.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p01] In this case, the principal index can be used to optimize storage for faster search with time-based filters.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p02] Qdrant supports full-text search for string payload.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p02] Full-text index allows you to filter points by the presence of a word or a phrase in the payload field.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p02] Full-text index configuration is a bit more complex than other indexes, as you can specify the tokenization parameters.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p02] Tokenization is the process of splitting a string into tokens, which are then indexed in the inverted index.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p02] See Full Text match for examples of querying with a full-text index.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p02] Tokenizers are algorithms used to split text into smaller units called tokens, which are then indexed and searched in a full-text index.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p02] In the context of Qdrant, tokenizers determine how string payloads are broken down for efficient searching and filtering.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p02] The choice of tokenizer affects how queries match the indexed text, supporting different languages, word boundaries, and search behaviours such as prefix or phrase matching.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p02] By default, full-text search in Qdrant is case-insensitive.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p02] For example, users can search for the lowercase term `tv` and find text fields containing the uppercase word `TV`.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p02] Case-insensitivity is achieved by converting both the words in the index and the query terms to lowercase.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p02] To use case-sensitive full-text search, configure a full-text index with `lowercase` set to `false`.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p02] When enabled, ASCII folding converts Unicode characters into their corresponding ASCII equivalents, for example, by removing diacritics.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p02] For instance, the character `ã` is changed into `a`, `ç` becomes `c`, and `é` is converted to `e`.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p02] Because ASCII folding is applied to both the words in the index and the query terms, it increases recall.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p02] For example, users can search for `cafe` and also find text fields containing the word `café`.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p02] ASCII folding is not enabled by default.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p02] To enable it, configure a full-text index with `ascii_folding` set to `true`.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p02] This enables the index to recognize and match different inflections or derivations of a word.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p02] Qdrant provides an implementation of Snowball stemmer, a widely used and performant variant for some of the most popular languages.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p02] For the list of supported languages, please visit the rust-stemmers repository.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p02] For full-text indices, stemming is not enabled by default.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p02] Stopwords are common words (such as “the”, “is”, “at”, “which”, and “on”) that are often filtered out during text processing because they carry little meaningful information for search and retrieval tasks.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p02] In Qdrant, you can specify a list of stopwords to be ignored during full-text indexing and search.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p02] This helps simplify search queries and improves relevance.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p02] You can configure stopwords based on predefined languages, as well as extend existing stopword lists with custom words.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p02] For full-text indices, stopword removal is not enabled by default.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p02] Phrase search in Qdrant allows you to find documents or points where a specific sequence of words appears together, in the same order, within a text payload field.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p02] This is useful when you want to match exact phrases rather than individual words scattered throughout the text.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p02] When using a full-text index with phrase search enabled, you can perform phrase search by enclosing the desired phrase in double quotes in your filter query.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p02] For example, searching for `"machine learning"` will only return results where the words “machine” and “learning” appear together as a phrase, not just anywhere in the text.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p02] See Phrase Match for examples of querying phrases with a full-text index.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p02] A vector index is a data structure built on vectors through a specific mathematical model.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p02] Through the vector index, we can efficiently query several vectors similar to the target vector.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p02] Qdrant currently only uses HNSW as a dense vector index.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p02] HNSW (Hierarchical Navigable Small World Graph) is a graph-based indexing algorithm.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p02] It builds a multi-layer navigation structure for an image according to certain rules.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p02] In this structure, the upper layers are more sparse and the distances between nodes are farther.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p02] The lower layers are denser and the distances between nodes are closer.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p02] The search starts from the uppermost layer, finds the node closest to the target in this layer, and then enters the next layer to begin another search.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p02] After multiple iterations, it can quickly approach the target position.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p02] In order to improve performance, HNSW limits the maximum degree of nodes on each layer of the graph to `m`.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p02] In addition, you can use `ef_construct` (when building an index) or `ef` (when searching targets) to specify a search range.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p02] And so in the process of creating a collection.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p02] The `ef` parameter is configured during the search and by default is equal to `ef_construct`.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p02] First, HNSW is well-compatible with the modification that allows Qdrant to use filters during a search.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p02] Second, it is one of the most accurate and fastest algorithms, according to public benchmarks.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p02] The HNSW parameters can also be configured on a collection and named vector level by setting `hnsw_config` to fine-tune search performance.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p02] Separately, a payload index and a vector index cannot completely address the challenges of filtered search.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p02] In the case of high-selectivity (weak) filters, you can use the HNSW index as it is.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p02] In the case of low-selectivity (strict) filters, you can use the payload index and do a complete rescore.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p02] However, for cases in the middle, this approach does not work well.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p02] On one hand, we cannot apply a full scan on too many vectors.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p02] On the other hand, the HNSW graph starts to fall apart when using filters that are too strict.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p02] Qdrant solves this problem by extending the HNSW graph with additional edges based on indexed payload values.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p02] Extra edges allow you to efficiently search for nearby vectors using the HNSW index and apply filters as you search in the graph.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p02] You can find more information on this approach in our article.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p02] In some cases, the additional edges built for Qdrant’s filterable HNSW may not be sufficient.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p02] These extra edges are added for each payload index separately, but not for every possible combination of payload indices.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p02] As a result, a combination of two or more strict filters might still lead to disconnected graph components.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p02] The same can happen when there are a large number of soft-deleted points in the graph.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p02] In such cases, use the ACORN Search Algorithm.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p02] When using ACORN, during graph traversal, it explores not just direct neighbors (first hop), but also neighbors of neighbors (second hop) when direct neighbors are filtered out.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p02] This improves search accuracy at the cost of performance.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p02] Not all payload indices may be intended for use with dense vector search.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p02] For example, when a collection contains both dense and sparse vectors, some payload fields may only be used to filter sparse vector searches.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p02] Since sparse vector search does not use the HNSW index, it is unnecessary to build extra edges in the HNSW graph for these fields.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p02] Creating extra edges adds indexing latency and increases the size of the HNSW graph, which consumes memory as well as disk space, so you may want to disable it for fields that do not require it.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p02] There may be cases when you need to rebuild the HNSW index, for example, when you create a new payload index and want to take advantage of filter-aware edges in the HNSW graph.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p02] To rebuild an HNSW index, make a small change to its HNSW configuration, for example by bumping `ef_construct` by `1`.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p02] This forces the optimizer to re-index all segments.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p02] Don’t immediately revert the value of `ef_construct` to its original value.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p03] Sparse vectors in Qdrant are indexed with a special data structure, which is optimized for vectors that have a high proportion of zeroes.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p03] In some ways, this indexing method is similar to the inverted index, which is used in text search engines.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p03] With Qdrant, you can benefit from a more compact and efficient immutable sparse index, which is constructed during the same optimization process as the dense vector index.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p03] This approach is particularly useful for collections storing both dense and sparse vectors.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p03] Unlike a dense vector index, a sparse vector index does not require a predefined vector size.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p03] It automatically adjusts to the size of the vectors added to the collection.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p03] For many search algorithms, it is important to consider how often an item occurs in a collection.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p03] Intuitively speaking, the less frequently an item appears in a collection, the more important it is in a search.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p03] This is also known as the Inverse Document Frequency (IDF).
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p03] It is used in text search engines to rank search results based on the rarity of a word in a collection.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p03] IDF depends on the currently stored documents and therefore can’t be pre-computed in the sparse vectors in streaming inference mode.
[src:qdrant/concepts-indexing-p03] In order to support IDF in the sparse vector index, Qdrant provides an option to modify the sparse vector query with the IDF statistics automatically.
[src:qdrant/documentation-overview] Whether you’re getting started with Qdrant Open-Source or Cloud, this brief primer will help you with understanding an overview of the platform.
[src:qdrant/documentation-overview] Vector search is a transformative information retrieval technique that goes beyond keyword matching to find data based on semantic meaning.
[src:qdrant/documentation-overview] It begins with **embedding models**, which convert unstructured data (text, images, audio) into **dense vector embeddings**, fixed-length lists of numbers that represent the data’s conceptual essence.
[src:qdrant/documentation-overview] These vectors are mapped into a high-dimensional **vector space**, where items with similar meanings are positioned closely together.
[src:qdrant/documentation-overview] This spatial organization allows a search for “climate change” to retrieve documents about “global warming,” even if the exact words differ.
[src:qdrant/documentation-overview] While dense vectors excel at capturing context, they can sometimes miss specific technical terms or unique identifiers.
[src:qdrant/documentation-overview] To bridge this gap, Qdrant also utilizes **sparse vectors** designed to capture precise **lexical matches** for specific keywords.
[src:qdrant/documentation-overview] The process of generating embeddings from unstructured data is called inference.
[src:qdrant/documentation-overview] On Qdrant Cloud, you can use Cloud Inference to let Qdrant generate embeddings on the server side.
[src:qdrant/documentation-overview] Alternatively, you can use a library like FastEmbed to generate embeddings on the client side.
[src:qdrant/documentation-overview] The search process itself revolves into the concept of **Top-K** retrieval.
[src:qdrant/documentation-overview] When a user submits a request, it is instantly transformed into a **query vector**.
[src:qdrant/documentation-overview] The engine then calculates the similarity between this query vector and document vectors, returning the “Top-K” closest matches, where K is a user-defined number representing the desired volume of results.
[src:qdrant/documentation-overview] This allows developers to fine-tune the balance between the breadth of the search and the precision of the answers.
[src:qdrant/documentation-overview] To deliver the most robust search experience, Qdrant enables **Hybrid Retrieval** with semantic and lexical search, which you can learn more about here.
[src:qdrant/documentation-overview] Qdrants operates in a client-server architecture, providing official client libraries for Python, JavaScript/TypeScript, Rust, Go, .NET, and Java.
[src:qdrant/documentation-overview] However, Qdrant exposes HTTP and gRPC interfaces to facilitate integration with virtually any programming language.
[src:qdrant/documentation-overview] (Qdrant organizes data around collections - named sets of points that you search within.
[src:qdrant/documentation-overview] Each point consists of a vector (numerical representation of your data) and optional payload metadata.
[src:qdrant/documentation-overview] Points are identified by 64-bit integers or UUIDs.
[src:qdrant/documentation-overview] Collections support multiple vector types per point, dense or sparse, and named vectors are used for storing different embedding types in a single point.
[src:qdrant/documentation-overview] When creating a collection, you specify vector dimensionality and distance metric for each of the named vectors you want to store.
[src:qdrant/documentation-overview] The HNSW index enables fast similarity search by building a graph structure that efficiently traverses similar vectors.
[src:qdrant/documentation-overview] Payload indexes can be created on specific fields to enable filtering during search, extending the HNSW graph for combined vector similarity and metadata filtering in a single pass.
[src:qdrant/documentation-overview] Data is organized into segments - storage units containing vectors and indexes - which are automatically optimized in the background.
[src:qdrant/documentation-overview] For distributed deployments, collections are split into shards, each containing its own segments.
[src:qdrant/documentation-overview] Qdrant collections are designed for horizontal and vertical scaling.
[src:qdrant/documentation-overview] Qdrant supports multiple deployment models to match different infrastructure and operational needs.
[src:qdrant/documentation-overview] The right option depends on your security constraints and operational model: Qdrant-managed infrastructure (Managed Cloud), shared responsibility with your own clusters (Hybrid Cloud), or full ownership and independence (Private Cloud or Open Source).
[src:qdrant/documentation-overview] The default configuration of Qdrant is sensible when you are starting to work on a POC or your side project.
[src:qdrant/documentation-overview] However, when transitioning to production and experiencing the growth of data size and concurrent users, your expectations regarding high availability, latency, or throughput will change.
[src:qdrant/documentation-overview] If you foresee scaling the service, you should build your system ready for these kinds of challenges from the outset.
[src:qdrant/documentation-overview] There are a few common scenarios you should be aware of, especially if you are taking your first steps with Qdrant, anticipate rapid growth soon, and want to make your system future-proof.
[src:qdrant/documentation-overview] Memory is a critical resource when scaling vector search.
[src:qdrant/documentation-overview] By default, Qdrant stores vectors in RAM for maximum search performance, but as collections grow to millions of vectors, keeping everything in memory becomes expensive.
[src:qdrant/documentation-overview] Put both on disk only when RAM is severely constrained, and ensure you have fast NVMe storage.
[src:qdrant/documentation-overview] Vector search alone can provide a decent search experience to your users; however, semantic similarity is rarely the only factor you have to consider.
[src:qdrant/documentation-overview] Embeddings won’t capture attributes such as price, and typically, a filter on a specific payload attribute has to be applied.
[src:qdrant/documentation-overview] To make that filtering effective, there are some specific Qdrant mechanisms you should be aware of, including with **payload indexes**.
[src:qdrant/documentation-overview] The payload index is a helper data structure that enables effective filtering on a particular payload attribute.
[src:qdrant/documentation-overview] It’s a concept familiar from relational databases, where we create an index on a column that we often filter by.
[src:qdrant/documentation-overview] Similarly, in Qdrant, you should also make a payload index on a field used for filtering.
[src:qdrant/documentation-overview] A unique aspect of the payload index is that it extends the HNSW graph, allowing filtering criteria to be applied during the semantic search phase.
[src:qdrant/documentation-overview] That means it’s a single-pass graph traversal, rather than pre- or post-filtering, which both have some drawbacks.
[src:qdrant/documentation-overview] The fact that a payload index extends the HNSW graph means it’s more efficient to create it before indexing the data, as the optimizer will need to build the graph once.
[src:qdrant/documentation-overview] However, in some cases, you may already have a collection with a lot of vectors and recognize a need to filter by a specific attribute.
[src:qdrant/documentation-overview] In such cases, you can still create a payload index, yet **it won’t immediately affect the HNSW graph**.
[src:qdrant/documentation-overview] ACORN is an additional mechanism that can improve the search accuracy if you have multiple high cardinality filters in your search operations.
[src:qdrant/documentation-overview] Vertical scaling has natural limits - eventually, you’ll hit the maximum capacity of available hardware, and single-node deployments lack redundancy.
[src:qdrant/documentation-overview] Optimize scaling with **sharding**, **replication**, and **segment configuration** options.
[src:qdrant/documentation-overview] Qdrant uses sharding to split collections across multiple nodes, where each shard is an independent store of points.
[src:qdrant/documentation-overview] A common recommendation is to start with 12 shards, which provides flexibility to scale from 1 node up to 2, 3, 6, or 12 nodes without resharding.
[src:qdrant/documentation-overview] However, this approach can limit throughput on small clusters since each node manages multiple shards.
[src:qdrant/documentation-overview] For optimal throughput, set `shard_number` equal to your node count (read more here).
[src:qdrant/documentation-overview] If you want to have better control over sharding, Qdrant supports custom shards.
[src:qdrant/documentation-overview] The replication factor determines how many copies of each shard exist.
[src:qdrant/documentation-overview] **For production systems, a replication factor of at least 2 is strongly recommended**.
[src:qdrant/documentation-overview] (Choosing a Replication Factor: RF=1 causes operational problems: node restarts make parts of your collection unavailable, and data loss is permanent without backups.
[src:qdrant/documentation-overview] Use RF=1 only for non-production workloads, development environments, or when data can be easily regenerated.
[src:qdrant/documentation-overview] RF=2 provides the optimal balance for most production deployments: data remains available during single-node failures, read operations benefit from load balancing, and rolling updates work without downtime.
[src:qdrant/documentation-overview] RF>2 is a throughput optimization for read-heavy workloads.
[src:qdrant/documentation-overview] More replicas distribute read operations across more nodes, increasing cluster throughput.
[src:qdrant/documentation-overview] Each shard stores data in multiple segments.
[src:qdrant/documentation-overview] A segment stores all the data structures of a subset of the points in a shard.
[src:qdrant/documentation-overview] Fewer segments create larger segments with better search throughput, as larger HNSW indexes require fewer comparisons.
[src:qdrant/documentation-overview] However, larger segments take longer to build and recreate, slowing writes and optimization.
[src:qdrant/documentation-overview] More segments mean faster indexing but lower search performance since queries scan more segments.
[src:qdrant/documentation-overview] Some of the collection-level operations may degrade performance of the Qdrant cluster.
[src:qdrant/documentation-overview] The OSS version does not enforce anything, but please consider enabling and configuring strict mode settings according to the application needs.
[src:qdrant/documentation-overview] Otherwise, some of the API calls may impact the performance of your cluster by using Qdrant in a suboptimal way.
[src:qdrant/documentation-overview] If you’re new to Qdrant, start with the free **Essentials Course**, which covers core concepts and best practices.
[src:qdrant/documentation-overview] For questions, troubleshooting, and community support, join the **Discord Community** - it’s the best place to get help from both Qdrant users and the core team.
[src:qdrant/documentation-overview] Paid customers have access to the **Support Portal** through the Qdrant Cloud Console, for direct technical assistance and priority response times.
[src:qdrant/documentation] Qdrant is an AI-native vector search and a semantic search engine.
[src:qdrant/documentation] You can use it to extract meaningful information from unstructured data.
[src:qdrant/documentation] Clone this repo now and build a search engine in five minutes.
[src:qdrant/documentation] Qdrant Edge is a lightweight, embedded vector search engine for in-process retrieval — no background services, minimal memory footprint, and no network required.
[src:qdrant/documentation] Built for robots, kiosks, mobile devices, and any environment requiring offline-capable AI search.
[src:qdrant/documentation] Learn how to manage your data, run powerful searches, and leverage inference to build AI-native applications.
[src:qdrant/documentation] Create collections, manage vectors, payloads, and storage.
[src:qdrant/documentation] Learn about indexing, quantization, and multitenancy.
[src:qdrant/documentation] Learn about similarity search, filtering, hybrid queries, and advanced retrieval techniques.
[src:qdrant/documentation] Configure dense, sparse, and multi-vector embeddings.
